Another idea on how to enable and disable individual test methods in 
a TestCase:  In the constructor (or setName method), check for method 
names that you DON&#39;T want to run, and redirect them to a &quot;no 
operation&quot; method.

Here&#39;s a TestCase that, based on a control flag, controls the 
execution of a given test method that the developer doesn&#39;t always 
want to be part of test runs.  It &quot;disables&quot; this method by 
redirecting to the &quot;__skip_test__&quot; method.

| package testing;
| import junit.framework.TestCase;
| public class TestDisableMethodByRedirection extends TestCase
| {
|     private static final boolean runOptionalTests = false;
|     public TestDisableMethodByRedirection(final String methodName) {
|         super(redirectTestMethods(methodName));
|     }
|     private static String redirectTestMethods(final String 
methodName) {
|         if (!runOptionalTests 
&& &quot;testThatWeWouldPreferNotToRun&quot;.equals(methodName))
|             return &quot;__skip_test__&quot;;
|         return methodName;
|     }
|     public void testThatRunsEveryTime() {
|         assertTrue(&quot;Normal tests -- which should always succeed.&quot;, 
true);
|     }
|     public void testThatWeWouldPreferNotToRun() {
|         assertTrue(&quot;Optional test -- because sometimes it fails.&quot;, 
false);
|     }
|     public void __skip_test__() {
|         int thisIsANicePlaceForADebuggerBreakPoint = 0;
|     }
| }
